label.value: abnormal protein localization to medial cortex in spores

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortex of a spore is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the medial cortex and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to medial cortex

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortex is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the medial cortex and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to medial cortex in spores

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortex of a spore is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein does not localize to, and is therefore absent from, a place where it is normally found.

definition.value: If this term is used, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

label.value: normal cellular calcium level during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell during a cellular response to salt stress is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased cellular calcium level during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell during a cellular response to salt stress is lower than normal.

label.value: increased cellular calcium level during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell during a cellular response to salt stress is higher than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of tacrolimus than normal.

label.value: normal nuclear morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is decreased.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of DNA measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which a protein kinase activity is absent.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, cell cycle arrest with replicated DNA

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell that enters the cell cycle but then undergoes cell cycle arrest with replicated DNA, and eventually dies.
A cell phenotype in which non-sporulating diploid cells become haploid, without undergoing meiosis, at a higher frequency than normal.

definition.value: Diploid cells may become haploid by chromosome loss, or by undergoing premature mitosis. Chromosome loss may also cause aneuploidy or cell death.

label.value: loss of viability at high temperature

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable when cells are grown at a temperature higher than standard.

definition.value: For S. pombe, high temperature usually means above 32 degrees C. Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown at high temperature, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to standard or low temperature is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: decreased protein level in germinating spore

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell is lower than normal during or just after spore germination. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleus localization is normal.
A septation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a septum that is not perpendicular to the long axis of the cell.

definition.value: Consider also annotating to 'angled actomyosin contractile ring' (FYPO:0002027) because if the contractile ring forms at an abnormal angle, the septum will also do so.

value.value: A septation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a septum closer to the new end of the cell (when the new end is not yet growing), instead of at the midpoint of the long axis.
A regulation phenotype in which regulation of vegetative cell growth is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal activation of monopolar cell growth

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the activation of monopolar cell growth, i.e. the initiation of growth at the old end of a cell following cell division, is abnormal.

label.value: activation of monopolar cell growth at either end

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the activation of monopolar cell growth may occur at either the new or old end of the cell, instead of exclusively at the old end, following cell division. A population of cells with this phenotype has a 1:1 mix of cells initiating growth at the new end and cells initiating growth at the old end.

label.value: normal activation of monopolar cell growth

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the activation of monopolar cell growth, i.e. the initiation of growth at the old end of a cell following cell division, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the switch from the monopolar to bipolar mode of cell growth (new end take-off; NETO) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: monopolar actin cortical patch localization to old end

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin cortical patches are localized to only the old end of a cell following cell division.

label.value: monopolar actin cortical patch localization to either end

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin cortical patches are localized to only one end of a cell following cell division; patches may localize to either the old or the new end. A population of cells with this phenotype has a 1:1 mix of cells with actin patches at the old end and cells with patches at the new end.
A physical cellular phenotype in which the mitotic spindle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) with respect to structure, composition, location, and orientation.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount, distribution, and morphology of cytoplasmic microtubules is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to cell division site

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the site of cell division is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the cell division site and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to cell cortex during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cell cortex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell adhesion phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells adhere to a substrate more strongly or to a greater extent than normal.
A colony morphology phenotype in which the outline of a colony growing on a solid surface is not symmetrical.
A colony morphology phenotype in which a colony growing on a solid surface has an abnormally glossy surface.
A septation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms a septum that is thicker than normal.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on glucose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing glucose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that this term encompasses growth under aerobic or semi-anaerobic conditions, whereas most cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which cells show increased sensitivity to heat shock. Heat shock is a form of heat stress in which cells are briefly exposed to a very high temperature.

label.value: normal growth on glycerol carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) in a medium containing glycerol as the carbon source.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of sulfide (S2-, also called acid labile sulfide) measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of sulfide (S2-, also called acid labile sulfide) measured in a cell differs from normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of sulfide (S2-, also called acid labile sulfide) measured in a cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of sulfide (S2-, also called acid labile sulfide) measured in a cell is higher than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to sulfide (S2-). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of sulfide ions that allows wild type cells to grow.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase activity is decreased.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell forms an equatorial microtubule organizing center in an abnormal location. The normal location is at the center of the cell.

label.value: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the microtubule cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a population of cells grows at the same rate as wild type.

label.value: normal vegetative cell population growth rate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a population of cells grow at the same rate as wild type in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

label.value: abnormal protein processing during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein processing is abnormal. Protein processing is the cleavage of one or more bonds within a protein that leads to the formation of mature, fully functional protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
